I feel like I connected to myself in a very Spiritual way in this practice. I always hear people talk about their Spiritual experiences with yoga, but today was the first time I really felt connected to that and finally understood what it meant, at least to me in my own way. 

Also, I'm not sure if this is a circulation thing,  the blood rushing to my limbs, or maybe it's that flow of energy as you might say, but I get soft, tingly sensations in my legs, feet, and arms every now and then. It doesn't feel uncomfortable like anything is getting pinched or cut off, but it's an interesting feeling that I've noticed for the past little while. It only started happening a few months into my practice. I've tried looking into it, but haven't found much so far, so was wondering if there was anyone else who maybe experienced similar sensations as this during your practice? If so, what did you make of it?

üôå I surrender to the pain. Rumi once said that "the cure for the pain is within the pain."  The more we resist suffering, the more difficult it becomes; but if we develop the strength to be with it, the suffering that most people try to run away from becomes a valuable guide or teacher. 

I have to remember that every antidote is created from the poison itself; that healing feeling so great because pain is so intense. My relationship with yoga, as with many in the community commenting here began with pain. In a way, suffering was a guide that lead me here when I realized I needed to be more accountable to my health. That no matter how terrible the situation, I have to keep going.

Pain is a friend that has joined me on the mat each day (whether emotional or physical) and each day he time I spend with it melts it away gradually like a masseuse working out a back knot. Yoga has been restoring my physical energy, and action has been restoring my courage and confidence. Namaste friend üôè

I've gotten a few days behind in getting to the mat; things got a bit off kilter last week. I have, however, been noticing the daily mantras, even if I haven't gotten to the practice until later. This one, "I surrender," turned out to be the theme for the day it was posted, in both positive and negative ways. I had some hard decisions to make, but I also got to notice and appreciate my friends' love, which got me through the difficult parts. The decision was a long time coming, but I'm sure the regular yoga practice has gotten me to where I'm ready to make it happen.

What advice would you give someone who struggles with this mantra due to having been oppressed. I am thinking for those who have had significant traumatic experiences and or those who are subject to racial/social/minority injustices. I imagine they may find it difficult to come to a calm mind repeating, "I surrender." I bring it up because my mind was preoccupied with the thought during the practice, and although it was enjoyable and I was able to modify the mantra to, "I surrender to the truth," it is always good practice to stay culturally aware.
